Aside from this, we will also get the terminal cash flow from the assets which can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Terminal CFA}&=\dfrac{\text{CFA* for Year 4}\times(1+\text{Growth rate})}{\text{WACC} -\text{Growth rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Terminal CFA}&=\dfrac{\$2,278,885.38 \times 1.03}{0.085-0.03}\\[15 pt]
&=\$42,667,308.03
\end{aligned}$$

The Terminal CFA is $\$42,667,308.03$

Since we already have the cash flow for Year 1 up to Year 4, we can now solve for the net present value, which gives us the value of the firm, using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\dfrac{\text{Year 1 Cash flow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^1}+\dfrac{\text{Year 2 Cash flow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^2}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Year 3 Cash flow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^3}+\dfrac{\text{Year 4 Cash flow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^4}
\end{aligned}$$

For this, the rate that we will use is the WACC which is $0.085$
